{
  "doc_id": "59978",
  "text": "In hierarchical testing, important error measures for summarizing the whole decision process include full-tree and outer-node FDR's [CITATION_1] , the focus level FDR [CITATION_2] , the mixed directional FDR [CITATION_3] , and the overall false discovery rate [CITATION_4] . Moreover, a hierarchical decision rule needs to fulfill a genuine logical relationship, that is, a case is rejected only if its parent node is rejected. Various methods have been developed for the adjustment of statistical significance according to the hierarchical structure, as well as the logical and error rate constraints; see [CITATION_5] , [CITATION_6] , [CITATION_7] , [CITATION_8] , and [CITATION_9] . Recent works on multiple comparison issue in multi-stage and sequential testing problems include [CITATION_10] , [CITATION_11] , [CITATION_12] , [CITATION_13] , Posch et al. (2009), Liang and [CITATION_14] , [CITATION_15] , [CITATION_16] , and [CITATION_17] . Hierarchical testing is also related to the control of directional errors in multiple testing; see [CITATION_18] for related theories and methodologies.",
